text: Spoiler alert: The rescue team fails to reach Matt Damon on mars and with only hours left before his limited supplies run out, he desperately seeks a solution.¬†  Matt's sensors pick up a mysterious wormhole orbiting saturn, at this point he is willing to take any option in order to survive even if it means travelling away from home. Using all of the ship's thrusters and boosters he slingshots the ship directly into the centre of the wormhole but in order to survive the journey, he puts himself into cryostasis.  A few years later crop blight and second Dust Bowl are slowly rendering Earth uninhabitable. Professor Brand (Michael Caine), a brilliant NASA physicist, is working on plans to save mankind by transporting Earth's population to a new home via a wormhole. But first, Brand must send former NASA pilot Cooper (Matthew McConaughey) and a team of researchers through the wormhole and across the galaxy to find out which of three planets could be mankind's new home.  :)

All in all the trailer doesn't have so many spoilers. there are so many twists and turns that they don't reveal. Honestly this trailer makes the movie look like it jumped from the pages which I am super excited about. There are so many direct quotes word for word from the book. "In your face Neil Armstrong." That's a direct quote from Watney in the book. there are so many others that are difficult to point out. Long story short, if you're interested in this movie, READ THE BOOK. text: Interesting that part of the video's text description above says "THE MARTIAN features a star studded cast that includes Jessica Chastain, Kristen Wiig, Kate Mara, Michael Pe√±a, Jeff Daniels, Chiwetel Ejiofor, and Donald Glover".  I noticed that two of the people in the official main list of major cast members (as shown during the final moments of the trailer video) are missing from that description, namely Sean Bean and Sebastian Stan. text: I read the book after I saw the trailer and I feel like it didn't meaningfully spoil the story or fun. The book has all these crazy adventures and setbacks that make you constantly wonder what's past the next Mars crater? It's these mini thrill rides that make the story memorable and really really awesome.  If you claim that this trailer spoiled the entire movie than we must have read a different book or just liked it for different reasons. This trailer doesn't cover the awesomeness that is The Martian. A full length movie will probably fall short to cover the great explanations, reasoning and adventures that Andy Weir put in the book.¬†  Apart from the not so scientific EVA suit I think the trailer is a great taste of what's to come and I can't wait to see how the movie handles (spoilers) Mark recovering pathfinder and retrofitting the rover and dealing with the exploded HAB and Mitch's outbursts... there's just so much to still look forward to!

text: OK. What Bozo came up with this animation of the Hermes? Take a close look at 1:45.¬†What are those ISS leftover bronzed solar panels for. Green energy credits! The Hermes is powered by a nuclear reactor. Which you would want at the farthest end of the ship, not you halfway to it.¬†Also by¬†the way, it needs a LOT of cooling so it doesn't go Fukushima and TMI,¬†with really big effective black body¬†black radiators, not bronze or pink or whatever. Where are they? Oh and the ion engines seem to be missing in action unless its that little thingy at the far end. Also, a bearing rotating hab structure? You mean like the bearings on reaction wheels, you know, the ones that fail all the time on the Hubble and crippled the Kepler telescope. Someone must have hooked up to Walt Disney's head for this 1950's space station resurrection. Simple ship axial spin would have taken care of the simulated centrifugal gravity.¬†Man spend some money to hire a space engineer consultant to make recommendations on what the print version of the Hermes would have actually looked like. Too bad if all the¬†excellent¬†realism in Weir's story¬†may¬†be botched by Hollywood's lack of reality based¬†technical comprehension.

text: Every 5-7 years movies about Mars appear from Hollywood. Almost every single one has the same plotline: An astronaut gets stuck on Mars, a team is sent to rescue. Team gets wiped out, astronaut makes it home alive. "How" they get home is different in each movie. For example (SPOILER ALERT) in¬†Mission to Mars "home" for the hero is the Alien's home world/galaxy (END SPOILER).¬†I believe these films is Hollywood's way of providing NASA, and more increasingly private commercial space ventures, the ability to gauge public interest in space and planetary travel. It would not surprise me if Elon Musk and/or Richard Branson financed this film.

text: I would be perfectly happy--both so that I won't have to endure the unreality of the situation while watching the movie--and for Ridley Scott's career, if he recalled the movie and reshot it with proper spacesuits. Anyone who knows that an MIT aerospace spacesuit engineer is working on a thinsuit can let the thickness of the suit pass--even though it does not look like a thinsuit, but what is completely and unequivocally unforgivable to people with a brain--especially space enthusiasts--is asking us to suspend disbelief over that confounded joke of a helmet-collar assemblage; the helmet does not link up with the collar, and it is completely obvious. It looks exactly like the stupid collar-helmet assembly from the Imperial Stormtroopers in Star Wars. But that is a fantasy of legendary proportions that our consciousness is set up to accept in such a way as it automatically sits right in our minds. If nothing else, Star Wars is for children, largely, but The Martian was written by a scholar of astronautics and aerospace and oribital¬†mechanics. This suit in the film is an insult to the back-breaking realism Andy Weir committed himself to and which makes this story what it is. I really wish NASA would have said no to it.

text: The Russian writer Mikhail Roshodnikov accused of plagiarism authors of the film "Martian" and filed a lawsuit against the company 20th Century Fox.  The story began back in 2007 when consumables invented story about the Russian astronaut in distress during a tornado suddenly erupted on Mars. In 2008 and 2009, the writer introduces the concept of the project the largest Russian and international companies. And he believes that's when the story hit Andy Uiru, author of "The Martian". In May 2011, we began filming the scenario Raskhodnikova that ended in August 2012. The truth is this film for some reason on the screens has not yet been released.  Then, in 2012, in the United States published a book "The Martian", written by the author debutant Andy Weir, and Drew Goddard which created the script for the new film by Ridley Scott. "When I read this book for me was the obvious similarities, because the entire outline of the plot and the characters are very similar," - said Mikhail consumables.  Lawyers film company 20th Century Fox have assured that Weir had never been to Russia, does not speak Russian and did not see the script Raskhodnikova. text: ... *Tremendously* entertaining film, and well acted.  There are a few areas that are sharply unrealistic, like the plastic holding in livable air pressure in the habitat, after the explosion. With 1% average density compared to Earth's, there would be a tremendous pressure difference between inside and outside. Example: it's impossible to open an airline hatch when the plane cabin is pressurized for cruising altitude, around 11 PSI (compared to 14.7 PSI for standard 1 atmosphere of pressure), putting a great outward force on the cabin main hatch, compressing the hatch sealing rim. Mars would be a much greater difference. Another would be the accoustic reflection of the engines back onto the main hatch of the rockets they use. On and on ... and yes, any scientist could science the **** out of these issues.  Yet it is still an exciting thriller.

text: Why shouldn't NASA have to offer Mars prizes, rewarding (for example) the first companies that successfully send and return humans to Mars? It could be done via:  ChallengeDOTgov  All sorts of Mars-related breakthroughs lend themselves to pro-entrepreneurial Mars prizes, but NASA's (predictably) not offering them. Why not?  Unfortunately NASA's a monopolistic, jealous govt. bureaucracy that feeds off of nearly $20 billion of our tax dollars per year. Its "workers" make load$ of money achieving relatively little, and they don't want to upset the apple cart. Innovation's needed though, due to the USA's bankruptcy:  usdebtclockDOTorg   The status quo isn't getting us to Mars for way too long, and they keep postponing the promised humans-to-Mars date too... The bureaucracy is parasitizing and will continue to do so until we demand better ways of spending our space exploration-related tax dollars. Are you up for demanding change?

text: Another shitty Hollywood film devoid of any possible truth. I am definitely not watching this garbage. It would take NASA decades to get back to full speed and do a Martian landing after being downsized by George W Bush. Plus Space X couldn't do any of this either. They just do satellites and try to send supplies to the International Space Station in unmanned crafts. The leading power in space is the Russian space agency –†–æ—Å–∫–æ—Å–º–æ—Å (Roscosmos). They have the best chance of doing something like this. The Russians (Soviets) had all of the firsts in space apart from the lunar landing in 1969. Yuri Gagarin, Sputnik, etc. Read about them on Wikipedia. Plus the US uses Russian rockets to send up satellites and our Astronauts fly from the Baikonur cosmodrome in Kazakhstan with the Russians in their –°–æ—é–∑ (soyuz) rockets. It's sad most Americans probably don't even know this. Russia 1 - USA 0.

Ridley Scott, the master of suspence leads us on a mundane castaway saga, one man versus a planet that is so lackluster that even Matt Damon plays his character as a bit irrelevent and goofy rather than as a loner unafraid to laugh in the face of danger who keeps the audience spellbound amid his unforeseen trials and tribulations. Damon's played his character in such a cartoonish manner, it reminded me of the old bugs bunny / space martian skit. What a shame...great book but the movie is hopelessly lost in space.

author: Rydell Garcia

text: Really like the "vibe" of this film. For a Ridley Scott film it's surprisingly good natured and funny. Matt Damon really finds his " inner nerd" and is so engaging. The fact that the film portrayed all the NASA people as competent was a nice touch. Most films would have made the final rescue turn into a botched " pull out the stops" set piece. Instead it just shows how smart, competent, and ballsy professionals can be actually that! I also liked the fact they played down the "pretend we're on Mars" stuff and just let us accept that it's just a story about a man stranded in a harsh environment. It's not Citizen Kane but still a solid film and Ridley's best in years.

text: Some people in the comment section, having severe conflicts about this movie and interstellar. In my opinion, I prefer 1.2001:ASO 2.interstellar 3.martian                   *Cause whenever we watch a film, we always wishes to think about a convincing ending. In the case of Martian, after the first 30 mins we can clarify that whatever it takes, they definitely gonna to rescue the protagonist from that stranded planet; i.e the climax is predictable. It's about how they gonna to save him and What are the struggles they are going to face in their path.                     *But in the case of interstellar, the matter is completely different, each and every frame of the film is intense and deals with new concepts. And the major highlight of interstellar is we can't even think about it's climax. And even though it is a convincing ending, we can't control our tears, due to it's plot twist. In addition to this, the RR of interstellar is completely different from other films made before it.                 So, in means of concept,story,screenplay and story telling, interstellar is incomparable with any other films other than 2001:ASO.                 The only similarity between interstellar and Martian is their plot (space).  Note: sorry for my Englishüòä

Why? 1) For the science - Mars has a lot scientists can learn from. 2) For the challenge - it will be one of the most challenging Human endeavors; we thrive off of challenges and decay without them. 3) For the future - Mars is the best place to establish a new branch of Humanity. Think about that and the enormous possibilities!
